RNA-seq in Bioconductor exercises

Rockefeller University, Bioinformatics Resource Centre

https://rockefelleruniversity.github.io/RU_RNAseq/

These are the first exercises are about alignment and counting in RNAseq.

In todays session we will work with some of the RNA-seq data of T-regulatory cells from Christina Leslies lab.

Sequencing data as a FastQ file can be found here.

Aligned data as a BAM file can be found here.

RNA-seq analysis.

  1. Download the above FastQ file for T-regulatory cells (replicate 2) - ENCFF070QMF.fastq.gz. Sample 100000 reads from file and produce our 3 standard plots - the DNA base occurence over cycles, histogram of quality scores and a boxplot of quality scores (for first 10000 reads sampled to save memory).
## class: ShortReadQ
## length: 100000 reads; width: 50 cycles

## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

  1. Remove reads with summed qualities less than 1000 and write to a new fastQ file.

  2. Align our filtered reads to the chromosome 10 of MM10 genome.

  3. Count the reads in our newly aligned and indexed BAM file mapping within genes. Plot a density plot of log 10 of reads counts across genes on chromosome 10. (Add 1 read to all counts to avoid log2 of zero)

  1. (Optional) Download and install Salmon.

Using Salmon, quantify transcript levels using reads from our filtered fastq.

  1. Read in the generated quant.sf file and plot log2 read counts by log10 TPM scores in a scatter plot.
